Programming distributed systems has never been easier, but making them perform well and efficiently exploit available resources remains difficult. Fast programs on a single host slow to a crawl when given more resources, while systems designed for scale squander resources on modest problems. We present Magpie, a programming model and framework for building high-performance, data-intensive applications. Magpie provides the straightforward guarantee that fast code remains fast when distributed. Because application code performs best when executed without interruptions, Magpie takes protocol off the critical path, automatically orchestrating the placement of data and computation to ensure uninterrupted local compute whenever possible. This flexibility requires extreme adaptivity, postponing all decisions about movement and placement until runtime. To support this finegrained adaptivity, distributed computations in Magpie are structured as compositions of lightweight transactions over distributed objects, both of which may move freely through the system. To showcase Magpie's performance and generality, we develop two very different libraries: a high-performance key-value store and a graph processing system. We show that Magpie achieves parity with or outperforms state of the art systems in both areas while providing richer guarantees.